Training: XGBoostTunePRAUC with: {'feat_trans_DropLowImportanceFeatures__option': 0, 'feat_trans_inst_income_ratio__option': 0, 'feat_trans_loan_purpose__option': 1, 'model__scale_pos_weight': 2, 'model__n_estimators': 50, 'model__min_child_weight': 3, 'model__max_depth': 5, 'model__learning_rate': 0.1, 'model__gamma': 0.05} XGBoostTunePRAUC: 1.1 seconds

The classification performance of all the models using the default 50% threshold is comparable (XGBoostTuneF1DummyDropFICO was included as a baseline).

We have chosen the XGBoostTunePRAUC configuration as our "production model" since it performs the best at predicting accurate probabilities (i.e. lowest log_loss).

XGBoostPRAUCBase (which achieves similar classification performance) uses a minimally processed dataset while XGBoostTunePRAUC uses several feature transformers (that were selected based on their impact on performances as part of our tuning process):

  • DropLowImportanceFeatures, dropping features with importance close to 0.0 simplifies the model and has no negative impact on performance
  • InstallementIncomeRatio, calculates the ratio between the income of the application and the expected installment size
  • LoanPurposeRiskTransformer, uses target encoding for the Loan Purpose column by calculating the default risk based on it.

We have tried multiple other feature transformers (see src/feature_engineering.py) but they had negative or no signficant positive impact on performance.

Evaluating Financial Returns/Performance¶

We'll use the model we have built to narrow down the sample of loans that have a lower risk to default.

This would be more useful to potential investors rather than the Lenders Club itself, they can use it in addition to the grade and other data provided by the Lenders Club to select the loans which not to invest it in.

In [13]:
def calculate_loan_portfolio_metrics(data):
    """
    Calculate loan metrics including total loan amount, total interest paid, total return percentage, and total loss.

    Args:
    - data: DataFrame with columns 'target__loan_status', 'pass__loan_amnt', and 'pass__int_rate'

    Returns:
    - DataFrame: A DataFrame containing the calculated metrics.
    """
    data = data.copy()
    total_loan_amount = data["pass__loan_amnt"].sum()

    # Total Loss - Sum of loan amounts for loans that defaulted
    total_loss = data.loc[data["target__loan_status"] == 1, "pass__loan_amnt"].sum()

    # Total Interest Paid - Only from loans that did not default
    data["interest_paid"] = data.apply(
        lambda x: (x["pass__loan_amnt"] * x["pass__int_rate"] / 100)
        if x["target__loan_status"] == 0
        else 0,
        axis=1,
    )
    total_interest_paid = data["interest_paid"].sum()

    data["expected_interest"] = data["pass__loan_amnt"] * data["pass__int_rate"] / 100
    expected_total_interest = data["expected_interest"].sum()

    total_return_percent = (total_interest_paid / total_loan_amount) * 100

    expected_return_percent = (expected_total_interest / total_loan_amount) * 100

    metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Total Loan Amount": [stats_utils.format_amount(total_loan_amount)],
            "Total Interest Paid": [stats_utils.format_amount(total_interest_paid)],
            "Expected Return %": [f"{expected_return_percent:2f}"],
            "Total Return %": [f"{total_return_percent:2f}"],
            "Total Loss": [stats_utils.format_amount(total_loss)],
        }
    )

    return metrics_df

The table below shows the total returns of all the loans in the dataset. We have to note that this is highly simplified because it assumes that all the loans that were defaulted on had to be completely written off but realistically this is not really the case:

  • all lenders are likely to make at least some payments before they default
  • defaulted loans can still be sold to third part for a fraction of the owed amount In future version of our model we should take these factors into account.

def estimate_financial_improvement(data, predictions):
    """
    Estimate financial improvement by comparing actual financial metrics to hypothetical
    scenarios where loans predicted to default were not issued. Values requiring conversion
    to millions are converted upfront.

    Args:
    - data: DataFrame with actual loan data, including 'target__loan_status', 'pass__loan_amnt', and 'pass__int_rate'.
    - predictions: Series or list containing model predictions corresponding to the data.

    Returns:
    - DataFrame: A DataFrame containing both actual and hypothetical financial metrics, with appropriate formatting.
    """
    data_with_predictions = data.copy()
    data_with_predictions["predictions"] = predictions

    total_loan_amount_actual = (
            data["pass__loan_amnt"].sum() / 1_000_000
    )  # Convert to millions
    total_interest_paid_actual = (
            data.apply(
                lambda x: (x["pass__loan_amnt"] * x["pass__int_rate"] / 100)
                if x["target__loan_status"] == 0
                else 0,
                axis=1,
            ).sum()
            / 1_000_000
    )
    total_loss_actual = (
            data.loc[data["target__loan_status"] == 1, "pass__loan_amnt"].sum() / 1_000_000
    )
    total_return_percent_actual = (
                                          total_interest_paid_actual * 1_000_000 / (
                                              total_loan_amount_actual * 1_000_000)
                                  ) * 100

    # Calculations for hypothetical when using the model scenario
    hypothetical_data = data_with_predictions[data_with_predictions["predictions"] == 0]
    total_loan_amount_hypo = hypothetical_data["pass__loan_amnt"].sum() / 1_000_000
    total_interest_paid_hypo = (
            hypothetical_data.apply(
                lambda x: x["pass__loan_amnt"] * x["pass__int_rate"] / 100, axis=1
            ).sum()
            / 1_000_000
    )  # Convert to millions
    total_loss_hypo = (
            hypothetical_data.loc[
                hypothetical_data["target__loan_status"] == 1, "pass__loan_amnt"
            ].sum()
            / 1_000_000
    )  # Convert to millions
    total_return_percent_hypo = (
                                        total_interest_paid_hypo * 1_000_000 / (total_loan_amount_hypo * 1_000_000)
                                ) * 100  # Recalculate to correct percentage if total_loan_amount_hypo > 0 else 0

    losses_avoided = total_loss_actual - total_loss_hypo
    interest_lost = total_interest_paid_hypo - total_interest_paid_actual
    total_applications_actual = len(data)
    total_applications_hypo = len(hypothetical_data)

    improvement_metrics = {
        "Total Loan Amount": [
            f"{total_loan_amount_actual:.4f}M",
            f"{total_loan_amount_hypo:.4f}M",
        ],
        "Total Interest Paid": [
            f"{total_interest_paid_actual:.4f}M",
            f"{total_interest_paid_hypo:.4f}M",
        ],
        "Total Return %": [
            f"{total_return_percent_actual:.2f}%",
            f"{total_return_percent_hypo:.2f}%",
        ],
        "Default Rate": [
            f"{data_with_predictions['target__loan_status'].mean():.2%}",
            f"{hypothetical_data['target__loan_status'].mean():.2%}",
        ],
        "Total Loss": [f"{total_loss_actual:.4f}M", f"{total_loss_hypo:.4f}M"],
        "Losses Avoided": [None, f"{losses_avoided:.4f}M"],
        "Interest Lost": [None, f"{interest_lost:.4f}M"],
        "Total Applications Accepted": [
            total_applications_actual,
            total_applications_hypo,
        ],
    }

    improvement_df = pd.DataFrame(
        improvement_metrics, index=["Actual", "Hypothetical"]
    ).T

    return improvement_df

We have selected only the loans which are unlikely to default using the default 50% threshold (note that the predicted probabilities don't directly indicate the likelihood of default):

Calculating Probability Thresholds¶

If we're using our binary classification model to assign grades to loans based on default probabilities we can't directly try to predict the grades from the source dataset.

Basically what we can do is to use the source dataset as a baseline and try to determine whether our model can outperform the method the Lending Club is using for determine grades, we'll try to maintain the same ratio of grades while trying to minimize the default risk for loans included in top grades (basically we want to make sure that's the spread of default risk between grades is maximized i.e. default risk for grade A is as close to 0% and for grade F as close to 100% as possible while also ensuring that the risk increased with continuously with grade)

# Assuming source_df_grades_summary and target_cm_data are already defined
# Sort probabilities for cumulative proportion mapping
target_cm_data_sorted = target_cm_data.probabilities.sort_values(by=1).reset_index(
    drop=True
)

source_df_grades_summary["Cumulative"] = source_df_grades_summary["Proportion"].cumsum()

sections = []

palette = sns.color_palette("YlOrRd", n_colors=len(source_df_grades_summary) - 4)

start_color = "grey"
colors = (
        [start_color] + palette + ["red"]
)  # Ensure "red" is used for the merged EFG section

i = 0
previous_cumulative = 0

efg_weights = source_df_grades_summary.loc["E":"G", "Counts"]
efg_risks = source_df_grades_summary.loc["E":"G", "Loan_Status_Ratio"]
weighted_avg_risk_efg = np.average(efg_risks, weights=efg_weights)

# Find thresholds in target_cm_data that match cumulative proportions
for grade, row in source_df_grades_summary.iterrows():
    if grade == source_df_grades_summary.index[0]:
        start = 0.0
    else:
        start = target_cm_data_sorted[1].quantile(previous_cumulative)

    end = target_cm_data_sorted[1].quantile(row["Cumulative"])

    #  merge grades E, F, G
    if grade == "E":
        continue
    elif grade == "F":
        continue
    elif grade == "G":
        label = "E-F-G Grade"
        color = "red"
    else:
        label = f"{grade} Grade"
        color = colors[i]

    if grade == "G":
        description = f"Expected D. R.: {weighted_avg_risk_efg:.1%}"
    else:
        description = f"Expected D. R.: {row['Loan_Status_Ratio']:.1%}"

    sections.append(
        {
            "label": label,
            "start": start,
            "end": end,
            "color": color,
            "description": description,
        }
    )
    if grade != "G":
        i += 1
    previous_cumulative = row["Cumulative"]
sections[-1]["end"] = 1.0

def map_grade_prediction_based_on_prop_fact(sections):
    def map_grade_prediction_based_on_prop(row):
        for section in sections:
            if section["start"] <= row < section["end"]:
                return section["label"].replace(" Grade", "")
        return None  # Return None if no matching range is found

    return map_grade_prediction_based_on_prop


predicted_grades = cm_target_model.test_data.probabilities[1].map(
    map_grade_prediction_based_on_prop_fact(sections)
)
predictions_with_data = pd.concat(
    [
        cm_target_model.test_data.x_test,
        predicted_grades.to_frame(name="predicted_grades"),
    ],
    axis=1,
)
results = (
    predictions_with_data.groupby("predicted_grades")
    .apply(proj_utils.calculate_metrics)
    .round(3)
)

display("Returns and Default Rate Based on Default Probability Model:")
results

We can see that while using our model to invested in the worst grades loans would lead to relatively poor returns investing in only in C grade or higher rated loans would provide better returns than using the Lenders Club's values to invest in the same loans:

  • Investing only in C loans would provide almost the same returns as the far riskier E-F-G loans using the original grades.
  • Only investing in A loans still yields ~10%, considering that the default rate is extremely low it might still be a preferable option to investing into high risk loans.

Basically using our model the investor would be able to minimize default risk while still getting decent returns i.e. if they only invested in loans with an estimated 10% default likelyhood or less using the original grades (so only A grade loans) they'd only make 6-7% while using our model this can be increased to more than 10%.

Limitations¶

We must take into account that this calculation is very simplified and therefore probably not accurate because, our model and calculations assume that Loss Given Default (LGD) is 100% and that Exposure at Default (EAD) is also 100% which is not accurate: - loans usually are not defaulted on immediately (i.e. some payments are almost always received) - most applicants who are unable to keep up with their payments are given some leeway and {PAYMENT PLAN} - failed loans are often sold to third parties for at least some fraction of the owed amount

Therefore, to provide a more accurate estimate and to figure out whether our model would actually be useful we'd need to incorporate the actual amounts received etc.
